mmas and competing options facing the Jews of this era as life in Eastern Europe underwent radical transformation.Using hitherto unexplored archival sources, memoirs, interviews, and materials from the vibrant interwar Jewish and Polish presses, Kalman Weiser investigates the rise and fall of Yiddishism and of Prylucki's political party, the Folkists, in the post-World War One era. Jewish People, Yiddish Nation reveals the life of a remarkable individual and the fortunes of a major cultural movement that has long been obscured.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aJewszPolandvBiography. 0aJewszPolandxCivilizationy20th century. 0aJewszPolandxIntellectual lifey20th century. 0aJewszPolandxPolitics and governmenty20th century. 0aPoliticianszPolandvBiography. 0aYiddish languagexPolitical aspectszPoland. 0aYiddish languagexSocial aspectszPoland. 0aYiddish languagezPolandxHistoryy20th century. 0aYiddishistszPolandvBiography. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266209440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442662094423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442662094.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK